{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78a7d5f8-dd98-45b8-b10e-301f32689245","content":"No workflow files found in the current directory. Since I can't inspect your specific workflow, here's a general guide for switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### Changes needed:\n\n**1. Add `id-token: write` permission to your job:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**2. Replace the `dotnet nuget push` step:**\n\nBefore (API key):\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg -s https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json -k ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}\n```\n\nAfter (trusted publishing):\n```yaml\n- uses: dotnet/nuget-push@v1\n  with:\n    source: https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nThis action handles the OIDC token exchange automatically — no secrets needed.\n\n**3. Configure NuGet.org:**\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Your Package → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new GitHub Actions trusted publisher, specifying your **repo**, **branch/tag filter**, and optionally the **workflow filename** and **environment**\n\n**4. Remove `NUGET_API_KEY`** from your repository secrets once trusted publishing is verified.\n\n### Optional but recommended:\nUse a GitHub **environment** (e.g., `nuget-publish`) with protection rules, and reference it in your job:\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: nuget-publish\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write\n      contents: read\n```\n\nThis scopes the OIDC token to that environment, which you can also pin on NuGet.org for tighter security.\n\nWould you like me to create or update a specific workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e0351a7-5662-4275-b85c-6702e546abdb","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"1429:2461FB:13CDF61:161518D:6A027A57"},"id":"1d07b875-9703-434c-b4a1-b9ad763ef340","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:54:57.869Z","parentId":"714f27a6-9b06-4a75-b669-8c376d357351"}
